WEBVTT

00:00:00.200 --> 00:00:02.120
Once you have defined a set of pointers to build

00:00:02.120 --> 00:00:05.290
your interpolation, you can apply it to any series of

00:00:05.290 --> 00:00:06.080
your choice.

00:00:07.290 --> 00:00:10.890
You can inspect the previously defined interpolation by pressing Ctrl

00:00:10.890 --> 00:00:11.520
D.

00:00:13.670 --> 00:00:17.320
Next, select the interpolation — referred to as the age

00:00:17.320 --> 00:00:20.480
model in paleoclimatology — and choose the series to be

00:00:20.480 --> 00:00:21.530
interpolated.

00:00:23.770 --> 00:00:27.190
Then select Apply Interpolation, depending on the method you want

00:00:27.190 --> 00:00:27.850
to use.

00:00:28.980 --> 00:00:30.910
A confirmation dialog appears.

00:00:31.950 --> 00:00:34.860
The interpolation is shown in red, and the series to

00:00:34.860 --> 00:00:37.510
which it will be applied are highlighted in green.

00:00:38.700 --> 00:00:41.790
The interpolated series appear below the original ones.

00:00:42.980 --> 00:00:47.210
Let’s inspect one interpolated series with Display Single or Ctrl

00:00:47.210 --> 00:00:47.810
D.

00:00:49.900 --> 00:00:52.160
You can see the new axis at the bottom, while

00:00:52.160 --> 00:00:55.610
the original axis remains at the top, now distorted.

00:00:55.610 --> 00:00:59.140
Note that the zoom function applies simultaneously to both axes

00:01:00.460 --> 00:01:03.580
The worksheet appears with an asterisk, indicating that it has

00:01:03.580 --> 00:01:04.820
been modified.

00:01:04.820 --> 00:01:06.540
Press Ctrl S to save it.

00:01:07.640 --> 00:01:09.920
In the next step, we will see how to display

00:01:09.920 --> 00:01:11.410
multiple series together.
